answer:
@Aaron Schüller-Ruhl  Can you send us the code you use to actually call the  search  function? Ideally we would also see the actual values, especially what is the specific  datetime_str . 
@Lauri Himanen maybe you have some ideas here? I agree that we would probably need the code to debug this further. Just as a tip, you should be able to actually simplify your queries like this:

 json
'query': {
    'and': [
        {'data.datetime#UMR_schemas.characterization.UMR_MPPTrackingParameters': datetime_str,
        {'data.device#UMR_schemas.characterization.UMR_MPPTrackingParameters': device,
    ]
} Great! The syntax I provided is the recommended way of querying data from custom schemas. I think we are missing proper documentation for creating API queries for these custom quantities, and you had to try and figure this out on your own, sorry for that. I will document this usage better somewhere in "How to use the API": https://nomad-lab.eu/prod/v1/staging/docs/howto/programmatic/api.html. All right, I might know what is going on. Our API transforms the JSON queries into some internal classes automatically before calling  search .  This might now be missing in your call. Could you try what happens if you do:

 python
from nomad.app.v1.models import WithQuery

search(
    owner='visible',
    query=WithQuery(query={
        'and': [
            {'data.datetime#UMR_schemas.characterization.UMR_MPPTrackingParameters': datetime_str},
            {'data.device#UMR_schemas.characterization.UMR_MPPTrackingParameters': device},
        ]
    }).query)
)

question:
I would like a way to explore the terms in a term widget that are not showing as the top x items. Currently the only way is to extend the size of the widget, which quickly becomes impractial. Is it possible to add a scrollbar to explore the less frequent appearing terms? 
Another idea I have is to state the number of total items, currently it only says e.g. "Showing top 3 items" and there doesn't seem to be a way to know the length of the list, except once the widget is large enough to show all items. So it would be nice to see e.g. "Showing top 3 of 300 items" or whatever the total number is.
@Lauri Himanen  How difficult would it be? Should I open an issue for this? Thanks!?

@Sarthak Kapoor and I encountered some issue when trying to run a plugin (which was created with the new plugin mechanism from the template showed in last weeks tutorial) locally on a nomad development environment. @Hampus Näsström helped us figure out what's the problem. More as documentation for others, multiple thing were found: 
- Plugins with the new mechanism don't need to be listed under the  plugins/options  section in the  nomad.yaml . It seems being  pip install ed is enough. - On the contrary, to list the plugin there leads to an error:  ValueError: ('The python package nomad_UBIK_plugin cannot be loaded.', AttributeError("'NoneType' object has no attribute 'get_filename'")) 
- Furthermore, the  plugins/include  section of the  nomad.yaml  apparently is an "include only". (I wasn't aware of that tbh!) The only way to get our plugin running was to omit it completely, which includes every available plugin. Then it is correctly shown in the metainfo browser or the about/information page. - We have not found a way yet to use it with the include section. Maybe somebody knows more?

